  <title>Cogl.AtlasTexture.new_from_bitmap</title>
  <synopsis><code mime="text/x-gjs">
function new_from_bitmap(bmp: <link xref="Cogl.Bitmap">Cogl.Bitmap</link>): <link xref="Cogl.AtlasTexture">Cogl.AtlasTexture</link> {
    // Gjs wrapper for cogl_atlas_texture_new_from_bitmap()
}
  </code></synopsis>
  <p>Creates a new <link xref="Cogl.AtlasTexture"/> texture based on data residing in a
@bitmap. A <link xref="Cogl.AtlasTexture"/> represents a sub-region within one of
Cogl's shared texture atlases.</p>  <p>The storage for the texture is not allocated before this function
returns. You can call <link xref="Cogl.Texture.allocate"/> to explicitly
allocate the underlying storage or preferably let Cogl
automatically allocate storage lazily when it may know more about
how the texture is being used and can optimize how it is allocated.</p>  <p>The texture is still configurable until it has been allocated so
for example you can influence the internal format of the texture
using <link xref="Cogl.Texture.set_components"/> and
<link xref="Cogl.Texture.set_premultiplied"/>.</p>  <p>&lt;note&gt;Allocate call can fail if Cogl considers the internal
format to be incompatible with the format of its internal
atlases.&lt;/note&gt;</p>  <p>&lt;note&gt;The returned <link xref="Cogl.AtlasTexture"/> is a high-level meta-texture
with some limitations. See the documentation for <link xref="Cogl.MetaTexture"/>
for more details.&lt;/note&gt;</p>
  <p>Since 1.16</p>
